    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna and it mentioned the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed and why it's so important?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! The pitot tube measures airspeed by capturing the air trapped between it and the aircraft's exterior, creating a pressure difference. This pressure difference is then compared to static air pressure, allowing the airspeed indicator to determine the speed at which the aircraft is moving through the atmosphere. It's essential because accurate airspeed measurements ensure safe and stable flight, helping pilots maintain optimal performance and avoid potentially dangerous situations.",
